public class EdiTraining : TrainingContentBase
{
    public EdiTraining(AppDbContext db, Dictionary<string, int> slugMap) : base(db, slugMap) { }

    public override async Task SeedAsync()
    {
        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Overview",
            Slug = "edi-overview",
            Summary = "What EDI is, the document formats you'll see, and how trading partners, the documents you exchange, and part-number matching work together in Forge.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","integrations"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## EDI Overview\n\nElectronic Data Interchange (EDI) lets your shop exchange business documents — purchase orders, invoices, shipping notices — with your customers and vendors electronically, instead of by paper, email, or retyping. As the person who handles EDI in the office, this is your workspace: it's where a customer's incoming order becomes a sales order in Forge without anyone keying it in by hand.\n\nThe EDI page lives under Admin > EDI. It gives you one place to set up the companies you trade with, watch every document that comes in or goes out, keep each partner's part numbers matched to yours, and fix anything that runs into a problem.\n\n### What EDI Does for You\n\nWhen a customer sends you a purchase order by EDI, it arrives as a document Forge reads and applies automatically — turning it straight into a sales order. No one retypes the part numbers, quantities, or dates. The reverse works too: when you ship an order, Forge can send the customer a ship notice or an invoice on its own.\n\nThe payoff for you is fewer keystrokes, fewer typos, and a clean record of every document you've traded with each partner.\n\n### The Documents You'll See\n\nEDI documents come in standard types. You'll mostly work with three, and they're named by number:\n\n- **850 — Purchase Order.** A customer's order coming in to you.\n- **856 — Ship Notice.** Tells your customer what's on the truck, going out from you.\n- **810 — Invoice.** Your bill for the order, going out from you.\n\nThe number is just a shorthand the whole industry uses — think of it as the document's name. Some partners use letter names instead (a customer's order may show up as ORDERS, an invoice as INVOIC), but you handle them the same way. Each partner is set up with a default format, and the page shows you which one every document used.\n\n### Trading Partners\n\nA trading partner is any company you swap EDI documents with — usually a customer, sometimes a vendor. For each one you set up:\n\n- **How they identify themselves** — a short code the partner gives you from their EDI setup sheet, so their documents get matched to the right partner. You type in what their sheet says.\n- **Format and how documents travel** — which document format they use, and whether documents move by a secure connection, a shared folder, a go-between service, email, or manual upload.\n- **How incoming documents are handled** — whether they process automatically or wait for you to review them first, and whether the partner wants a receipt sent back confirming each document arrived.\n- **Who they are in Forge** — you can link a partner to an existing customer or vendor so their orders land on the right account automatically.\n\n### The Documents Log\n\nEvery document you exchange shows up as a row you can open. Each one tells you:\n\n- **Which partner** it's with, and whether it **came in or went out**.\n- **What kind** of document it is — an 850, an 810, an 856.\n- **Where it is** — a colored label shows whether it's still processing, went through cleanly, or hit a problem.\n- **What it created** — the sales order or purchase order it turned into, once it's applied.\n- **What went wrong**, if anything — a failed document shows a plain-language reason and a Retry button so you can send it back through.\n\n### Matching Their Part Numbers to Yours\n\nCustomers order using *their* part numbers, not yours. So each partner has a **part-number list**: a simple two-column table that says \"when this partner says part X, they mean our part Y.\" Keep it current and every incoming order lines up with your catalog on its own.\n\nYou open the list from the partner's row on the Trading Partners tab. It's a plain typed grid — one row per pair, their number on the left, yours on the right. As you type your part number, it looks it up in your catalog and shows the part's description so you know you matched the right one; a number that matches nothing is flagged so you catch the gap before an order arrives.\n\nYou can fill it in two ways:\n\n- **Type it in** — for a handful of parts, add rows and type each pair.\n- **Import a spreadsheet** — for a long cross-reference, import a two-column file (their number, your number). Re-importing an updated file refreshes the existing rows instead of duplicating them.\n\nThe list is per-partner because every customer numbers parts differently.\n\n### How an Incoming Order Matches Up\n\nWhen a customer sends a purchase order (an **850**), each order line carries *their* part number. Forge matches each line before it becomes a sales order line:\n\n1. The partner's part number on the line is looked up in **that partner's** part-number list.\n2. If there's a match, the sales order line is created against your catalog part — automatically.\n3. If the line has no match yet — or points at a part number you don't stock — the line is **still created**, but it keeps the partner's number in the order-line notes so you can finish the match by hand.\n\nNothing gets dropped. An incomplete list just means a little manual matching, not a lost order — which is exactly why keeping each partner's list current pays off on every order that comes in. This is a straight number swap. Converting units or pack quantities isn't part of it today; a partner who needs that is a setup conversation, not something you handle in this grid.\n\n### How Documents Travel\n\nThere are a few ways documents move between you and a partner. You pick one per partner:\n\n- **Secure connection (AS2)** — a direct, encrypted link. The partner sends back a signed receipt proving each document arrived. Common for high-volume partners.\n- **Shared folder (SFTP)** — documents are dropped into folders on a secure server both sides use. Simple and reliable.\n- **Go-between service (VAN)** — a service like SPS Commerce or TrueCommerce sits in the middle and routes documents for you. Connect once, reach many partners.\n- **Email** — documents as email attachments. Least automated; good for the occasional partner or as a backup.\n- **Direct connection to their system** — a modern option some large customers offer.\n- **Manual** — you upload and download documents yourself in the app. Best while you're setting a partner up and testing.\n\n### Automatic vs. Review-First\n\nWhen a partner is set to process automatically, an incoming document is read and applied to your orders on its own. When it's set to review-first, the document waits so you can look it over before it's applied. Turn automatic on once you trust a partner's documents; keep it off while you're still testing.\n\n### When EDI Earns Its Keep\n\n- When a customer or vendor requires electronic documents to do business with you\n- When you want to stop hand-keying the same recurring orders\n- When you need a clean record of every document traded with a partner\n- When a customer expects an automatic receipt each time a document arrives","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI — Guided Tour",
            Slug = "edi-walkthrough",
            Summary = "A guided tour of the Admin > EDI page: sub-tabs, trading partner table, partner dialog, transaction list, filters, transaction detail, and retry.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 2,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/admin/edi","startButtonLabel":"Tour EDI","steps":[{"element":".edi-panel .tab-bar","popover":{"title":"The Two Tabs","description":"This page has two tabs. Trading Partners is where you set up the companies you swap documents with. Transactions shows every document that has come in or gone out. Click a tab to switch between them.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".edi-panel__toolbar .action-btn--create","popover":{"title":"Add a Trading Partner","description":"Click here to add a company you'll exchange documents with. You'll give it a name, pick the document format and how documents travel between you, and set whether they process automatically. You can also link the partner to a customer or vendor.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-data-table[tableId='edi-partners']","popover":{"title":"Your Partners","description":"This table lists every partner you've set up. Each row shows the partner's name, its linked customer or vendor, the document format, how documents travel, how many documents you've exchanged, how many had errors, and whether it's active. Click a heading to sort.","side":"top"}},{"element":".edi-panel__actions","popover":{"title":"Buttons on Each Row","description":"Every partner row has four buttons: test the connection, open the part-number list that matches their part numbers to yours, edit the partner, and remove it. When you edit, the password box is left empty — leave it empty to keep the saved one, or type a new one to change it.","side":"left"}},{"element":".gap-note","popover":{"title":"Matching Their Parts to Yours","description":"This note points to the part-number list on each partner. It matches the part numbers a partner uses to your own, so incoming orders line up with your catalog automatically. Open it to add matches by hand or import a spreadsheet.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".tab:nth-child(2)","popover":{"title":"Transactions Tab","description":"Switch here to see every document exchanged. Each row shows the partner, whether it came in or went out, the document type, its status, what it created, when it arrived, and how many times it was retried.","side":"bottom"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Field Reference (QuickRef) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Field Reference",
            Slug = "edi-field-reference",
            Summary = "Complete reference for every field, status, format, transport method, button, and validation rule in the EDI module.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 3,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"EDI Field Reference","groups":[{"heading":"Trading Partner Form Fields","items":[{"label":"Name (required)","value":"The name you'll recognize this partner by, such as 'Acme Corp EDI'. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"Qualifier ID (required)","value":"A short code that says how the partner's ID is formatted. Common ones are '01' for a DUNS number, '08' for a UCC/EAN code, '12' for a phone number, and 'ZZ' when you and the partner simply agree on a code. Defaults to 'ZZ'."},{"label":"Qualifier Value (required)","value":"The partner's actual ID — the DUNS number, phone number, or agreed code that goes with the Qualifier ID above. Up to 100 characters."},{"label":"Default Format (required)","value":"The document format this partner uses. X12 is the North American standard; EDIFACT is the international one. Defaults to X12."},{"label":"Transport Method (required)","value":"How documents travel between you and the partner: AS2, SFTP, a VAN service, email, a direct connection, or manual upload. Defaults to Manual."},{"label":"Auto Process (on/off)","value":"When on (the default), incoming documents are read and applied automatically. When off, they wait at Received so you can review them first."},{"label":"Require Acknowledgment (on/off)","value":"When on (the default), the system automatically sends a receipt back to the partner confirming each document arrived. Defaults to on."},{"label":"Notes","value":"Optional free-form notes about the partner — contact info, special requirements, or anything worth remembering."}]},{"heading":"Trading Partner Table Columns","items":[{"label":"Name","value":"The partner's name. Click to sort."},{"label":"Customer","value":"The linked customer, or a dash if none is linked."},{"label":"Vendor","value":"The linked vendor, or a dash if none is linked."},{"label":"Format","value":"The document format: X12 or EDIFACT."},{"label":"Transport","value":"How documents travel: AS2, SFTP, a VAN, email, a direct connection, or manual."},{"label":"Txns","value":"How many documents you've exchanged with this partner in total."},{"label":"Errors","value":"How many documents ran into a problem. Shown as a red label when there are any."},{"label":"Active","value":"A green check when the partner is active, a gray mark when it isn't."},{"label":"Actions","value":"Four buttons: test the connection, open the part-number list, edit the partner, and remove it."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Table Columns","items":[{"label":"Partner","value":"The trading partner this document came from or went to."},{"label":"Dir","value":"Whether the document came in or went out. You can filter by this."},{"label":"Set","value":"The document type, shown as a number — for example an 850 (the customer's purchase order), an 810 (an invoice), or an 856 (a ship notice)."},{"label":"Control #","value":"The tracking number that identifies this document."},{"label":"Status","value":"A colored label showing where the document is in processing. You can filter by this."},{"label":"Entity","value":"What the document created in the system, such as a sales order or purchase order, or a dash if it hasn't been applied yet."},{"label":"Received","value":"The date and time the document arrived."},{"label":"Retries","value":"How many times a failed document has been retried."},{"label":"Actions","value":"A Retry button appears only on documents that ran into an error."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Detail Fields","items":[{"label":"Partner","value":"The trading partner this document is with."},{"label":"Direction","value":"Whether the document came in or went out."},{"label":"Document Type","value":"What kind of document it is, such as an 850 (a purchase order), an 810 (an invoice), or an 856 (a ship notice)."},{"label":"Status","value":"A colored label showing where the document is in processing."},{"label":"Error Message","value":"When a document fails, this red box explains what went wrong."},{"label":"Original Document","value":"The document exactly as it came in or went out, in its original form — handy if you need to confirm what the partner actually sent."},{"label":"Read-Out Fields","value":"The same document laid out as tidy, labeled fields once the system has read it, so you can see the parts, quantities, and dates at a glance."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Statuses","items":[{"label":"Received (blue)","value":"The document arrived but hasn't been processed yet. This is where every incoming document starts, and where it waits if Auto Process is off."},{"label":"Parsing (yellow)","value":"The system is reading the document and pulling out its fields."},{"label":"Parsed","value":"The system finished reading the document successfully."},{"label":"Validating (yellow)","value":"The system is checking the document against your rules."},{"label":"Validated","value":"The checks passed. The document is ready to apply."},{"label":"Processing (yellow)","value":"The system is applying the document — creating or updating things like sales orders and purchase orders."},{"label":"Applied (green)","value":"Done. The document went through and the related record was created or updated. The Entity column shows what it made."},{"label":"Error (red)","value":"Processing failed somewhere. The error message explains why, and a Retry button appears."},{"label":"Acknowledged (gray)","value":"A receipt confirming this document arrived has been sent back to the partner."},{"label":"Rejected (red)","value":"The document was turned away during checking — the data didn't meet the rules, or the partner's part numbers couldn't be matched."}]},{"heading":"EDI Formats","items":[{"label":"X12","value":"The dominant standard in North America. Document types are numbered — for example 850 (purchase order), 810 (invoice), 856 (ship notice), and 855 (order acknowledgment)."},{"label":"EDIFACT","value":"The international standard, used widely in Europe and Asia. Document types have letter names like ORDERS (purchase order), INVOIC (invoice), and DESADV (ship notice)."}]},{"heading":"Transport Methods","items":[{"label":"AS2","value":"The most common business-to-business method. Documents are encrypted and signed, and the partner sends back a signed receipt confirming delivery."},{"label":"SFTP","value":"Secure file transfer. Documents are dropped into folders on a secure server that both sides share. Simple and reliable."},{"label":"VAN","value":"A go-between service (such as SPS Commerce or TrueCommerce) that routes documents between you and your partners and handles format differences for you."},{"label":"Email","value":"Documents sent as email attachments. Not very automated — usually for low-volume partners or as a backup."},{"label":"API","value":"A direct connection to the partner's system. A modern alternative to the traditional methods."},{"label":"Manual","value":"You upload and download documents yourself in the app. Best for testing, low-volume partners, or getting started before you automate."}]},{"heading":"SFTP Transport Fields (shown only when Transport = SFTP)","items":[{"label":"Host","value":"The address of the secure server where this partner exchanges files."},{"label":"Port","value":"The port to connect on. Defaults to 22."},{"label":"Username","value":"The login name for the server account."},{"label":"Password","value":"Type the password. It's stored securely and never shown again. When you come back to edit, this box is empty — leave it empty to keep the saved password, or type a new one to change it."},{"label":"Outbound Directory (we send)","value":"The folder on the server where outgoing documents are placed."},{"label":"Inbound Directory (we poll)","value":"The folder on the server checked for incoming documents."},{"label":"Password-kept-on-edit hint","value":"A note in the SFTP section: when a password is already saved it reads 'A password is stored. Leave blank to keep it; type a new one to replace it'; otherwise it reads 'The password is stored securely and never shown again.'"}]},{"heading":"Part-Number List","items":[{"label":"What it is","value":"A two-column list, one per partner, that matches the partner's part numbers to yours. Open it from the partner's row. You fill it in by typing — it's not a code editor."},{"label":"Partner Part #","value":"The part number the partner uses on their documents."},{"label":"Our Part #","value":"Your own part number that it matches to."},{"label":"Resolves To","value":"When your part number matches a real part in your catalog, its description shows here. If nothing matches, you'll see a 'No matching part' warning — the row still saves, but an order line using it comes in unmatched until that part exists."},{"label":"Add Row","value":"Adds a blank row so you can type a new pair."},{"label":"Import CSV","value":"Imports a two-column spreadsheet all at once. Re-importing an updated file refreshes existing rows instead of duplicating them. See the CSV Import reference."},{"label":"Save","value":"Saves the whole list and reloads it with fresh catalog matches."},{"label":"Delete row","value":"Removes that pair from the list. Takes effect when you save."}]},{"heading":"Buttons and Actions","items":[{"label":"New Trading Partner","value":"The main button on the Partners tab. Opens the form to add a partner."},{"label":"Test Connection","value":"On each partner row. Checks that the connection to the partner works and tells you whether it succeeded."},{"label":"Part-Number List","value":"On each partner row. Opens the list that matches the partner's part numbers to yours, where you can type entries or import a spreadsheet."},{"label":"Edit Partner","value":"On each partner row. Opens the partner form filled in with current values. The password box opens empty — leave it empty to keep the saved password, or type a new one to change it."},{"label":"Delete Partner","value":"On each partner row. Removes the partner."},{"label":"Retry Transaction","value":"On documents that ran into an error. Sends the document back through processing and confirms it's queued."},{"label":"View Transaction","value":"Click any document row to open its detail view — partner, direction, type, status, the original document, the read-out fields, and any errors."},{"label":"Close (transaction detail)","value":"Closes the document detail view."},{"label":"Save / Create (partner form)","value":"Saves the partner. It's turned off while the form is incomplete or saving. When it's off, a red warning triangle sits to its left — click it to see which fields still need attention."},{"label":"Cancel (partner form)","value":"Closes the form without saving."}]},{"heading":"Validation Rules","items":[{"label":"Name","value":"Required. Up to 200 characters."},{"label":"Qualifier ID","value":"Required. Up to 10 characters. Defaults to 'ZZ'."},{"label":"Qualifier Value","value":"Required. Up to 100 characters."},{"label":"Default Format","value":"Required. Must be X12 or EDIFACT."},{"label":"Transport Method","value":"Required. Must be one of AS2, SFTP, VAN, email, a direct connection, or manual."},{"label":"Submit button","value":"Turned off while the form is incomplete or saving. When it's off, a red warning triangle sits to its left — click it to see which fields need attention."}]},{"heading":"Transaction Filters","items":[{"label":"Direction filter","value":"Choose All (the default), incoming, or outgoing to narrow the list by which way the document went."},{"label":"Status filter","value":"Choose All (the default) or a single status — Received, Parsing, Parsed, Processing, Applied, Error, Acknowledged, or Rejected."},{"label":"Filter behavior","value":"Picking any filter updates the list right away."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Knowledge Check (Quiz) ───────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "EDI Knowledge Check",
            Slug = "edi-quiz",
            Summary = "Test your knowledge of the EDI module: formats, trading partners, transactions, mappings, statuses, and transport methods.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"edi1","text":"A new customer requires EDI document exchange for purchase orders. Where do you set this up in Forge?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Customers, open the customer detail, and enable the EDI toggle"},{"id":"b","text":"Navigate to Admin > EDI, click New Trading Partner, and configure the partner with the customer's EDI identifiers, format, and transport method","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Create a new integration in Admin > Integrations and select EDI as the type"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Admin > Settings and add the customer's EDI credentials to the system settings"}],"explanation":"Trading partners are managed under Admin > EDI. Click New Trading Partner and fill in the name, qualifier ID/value, default format (X12 or EDIFACT), transport method, and processing rules. You can link the partner to an existing Customer record."},{"id":"edi2","text":"What is the difference between X12 and EDIFACT?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"X12 is for invoices only, EDIFACT is for purchase orders only"},{"id":"b","text":"X12 is the North American standard, naming its document types by number (like 850, 810); EDIFACT is the international standard, naming them with letters (like ORDERS, INVOIC)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"X12 is newer and replaces EDIFACT, which is deprecated"},{"id":"d","text":"X12 only works with AS2 transport, while EDIFACT only works with SFTP"}],"explanation":"X12 is the standard used across North America; its document types are named by number (850 for a purchase order, 810 for an invoice). EDIFACT is the international one, used mostly in Europe and Asia; its document types have letter names instead (ORDERS, INVOIC). Both are in active use, and you handle documents in either format the same way — the page tells you which one each partner uses."},{"id":"edi3","text":"You see a transaction in the Transactions tab with status 'Error' (red chip). What action can you take?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the transaction and ask the partner to resend"},{"id":"b","text":"Click the transaction row to view the error details, then click the Retry button to re-queue it for processing","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Change the status manually to Applied to force it through"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — error transactions are permanently failed and must be handled outside Forge"}],"explanation":"A document in Error status shows a Retry button in the actions column. Click the row to read the plain-language error and see the original document, then click Retry to send it back through processing. The retries count tells you how many attempts have been made."},{"id":"edi4","text":"What does the 'Auto Process' toggle on a trading partner control?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether outbound documents are sent automatically or queued for manual review"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether inbound documents are automatically parsed, validated, and applied, or held at Received status for manual review","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the partner's connection is tested automatically every hour"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether duplicate documents from this partner are automatically rejected"}],"explanation":"When Auto Process is ON (the default), an incoming document is read, checked, and applied to your orders on its own — you'll see it land as Applied. When OFF, the document stops at Received and waits for you to review it before it goes any further. Turn it on for partners you trust; keep it off while you're still testing a new one."},{"id":"edi5","text":"A trading partner's Qualifier ID is set to 'ZZ'. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The partner uses a ZIP code as their identifier"},{"id":"b","text":"The identifier type is 'Mutually Defined' — the Qualifier Value is a code agreed upon by both parties","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The partner has not been fully configured yet and 'ZZ' is a placeholder"},{"id":"d","text":"The partner uses a DUNS number for identification"}],"explanation":"'ZZ' is the EDI qualifier code for 'Mutually Defined,' meaning both trading partners have agreed on the format and meaning of the Qualifier Value. It is the most common qualifier when partners don't use a standard identifier like DUNS ('01') or UCC/EAN ('08'). It is also the default in Forge."},{"id":"edi6","text":"A customer sends EDI purchase orders using their own part numbers, not yours. How do you make inbound 850 lines match your catalog automatically?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Ask the customer to renumber their parts to match your catalog"},{"id":"b","text":"Open that partner's part-number list and add rows — or import a spreadsheet — pairing each of their part numbers with yours","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Rename your catalog parts to match the customer's numbering scheme"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — EDI always matches on part description, so numbering doesn't matter"}],"explanation":"Each partner has its own part-number list, opened from its row on the Trading Partners tab. It's a plain two-column table — their number on the left, yours on the right — that you type in by hand or fill by importing a spreadsheet. Incoming 850 order lines match through this list before they become sales order lines; a line with no match yet is still created, but it keeps the partner's number in the order-line notes so you can finish it by hand."},{"id":"edi7","text":"You want to see only inbound transactions that failed processing. How do you filter the transaction list?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Set the Direction filter to Inbound and the Status filter to Error","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Click the column header for Status and type 'Error' in the search box"},{"id":"c","text":"Use the search bar at the top and type 'Inbound Error'"},{"id":"d","text":"Switch to the Partners tab and look for partners with error counts > 0"}],"explanation":"The Transactions tab has two filter dropdowns at the top: Direction and Status. Set Direction to 'Inbound' and Status to 'Error' to see exactly the failed inbound transactions. The list refreshes immediately when you change either filter."},{"id":"edi8","text":"Which way of moving documents is a direct, encrypted connection where the partner sends back a signed receipt confirming each document arrived?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A shared folder (SFTP)"},{"id":"b","text":"Email"},{"id":"c","text":"A secure connection (AS2)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"A go-between service (VAN)"}],"explanation":"A secure connection (AS2) is a direct, encrypted link between you and the partner, with no middleman. Its defining feature is the signed receipt the partner returns proving each document was delivered. It's the usual choice for high-volume partners where you want proof of delivery on every document."},{"id":"edi9","text":"A trading partner has 'Require Acknowledgment' turned on. What happens when a document comes in from them?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Forge automatically sends a receipt back to the partner confirming the document arrived and was handled","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Forge emails the admin that a document was received"},{"id":"c","text":"The document is held until someone clicks an Acknowledge button"},{"id":"d","text":"The partner's system marks it delivered with no action from Forge"}],"explanation":"When Require Acknowledgment is on, Forge automatically sends the partner a receipt confirming their document arrived and was handled. You don't do anything — it happens on its own. The receipt is linked back to the original document so you have a clear trail of what was confirmed."},{"id":"edi10","text":"What does the 'Test Connection' button on a trading partner row do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Sends a test document to the partner to check the whole process end to end"},{"id":"b","text":"Checks that the connection to the partner is working and tells you whether it succeeded","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Sends the partner an email asking them to confirm they're set up"},{"id":"d","text":"Switches the partner between test mode and live mode"}],"explanation":"Test Connection checks that Forge can reach the partner over whatever way you've set up for them — a secure connection, a shared folder, a go-between service. It pops up a success message if the connection works, or an error message telling you what failed if it doesn't. It doesn't send any real documents, so it's safe to click while you're setting a partner up."},{"id":"edi11","text":"A document shows a status of 'Acknowledged' (gray label). What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The document arrived and is waiting for someone to acknowledge it before processing"},{"id":"b","text":"A receipt has been sent back to the partner confirming their document arrived","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The sales order it created has been confirmed by the warehouse team"},{"id":"d","text":"The document failed but was noted as a known issue that won't be retried"}],"explanation":"Acknowledged means a receipt has gone back to the partner confirming their incoming document arrived and was handled. It's the automatic confirmation the partner asked for when Require Acknowledgment is on, and it's linked to the original document so you have a clean trail."},{"id":"edi12","text":"You need to set up EDI for a low-volume vendor who sends purchase orders occasionally. You are still configuring the integration. Which transport method is most appropriate to start with?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"AS2 — it is the industry standard and should be used from day one"},{"id":"b","text":"Manual — upload and download documents through the Forge UI while you configure and test the full integration","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"VAN — always use a VAN for low-volume partners to reduce complexity"},{"id":"d","text":"A direct connection to their system — set it up right away for maximum speed"}],"explanation":"Manual lets you upload and download documents yourself in the app. It's the best choice while you're setting a partner up and testing, because it needs nothing arranged in advance. Once you trust that their documents come through cleanly, switch the partner to an automated method — a secure connection, a shared folder, or a go-between service."}]}"""
