            Title = "EDI Part-Number Translation",
            Slug = "edi-part-number-translation",
            Summary = "How the per-partner Part-Number Map translates a trading partner's part numbers to yours so inbound 850 lines match your catalog — building the map by hand or importing a CSV.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","admin","parts","translation"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## EDI Part-Number Translation\n\nTrading partners order using *their* part numbers, not yours. The **Part-Number Map** is how Forge bridges that gap: a per-partner table that pairs each partner part number with the matching part number in your catalog. Keep it current and inbound purchase orders match your parts automatically — no one retypes anything.\n\nThis is a plain typed two-column grid — you fill it in the way you'd fill in a spreadsheet, not a code editor. You manage one map per trading partner because every customer numbers parts differently.\n\n### Where to find it\n\n1. Go to **Admin > EDI** and stay on the **Trading Partners** tab.\n2. Find the partner in the table.\n3. In that row's action buttons, click the **Part-Number Map** action — the swap-arrows icon, between Test Connection and Edit.\n4. The Part-Number Map dialog opens, titled with the partner's name.\n\n### Reading the grid\n\nEach row has three meaningful columns plus a delete action:\n\n- **Partner Part #** — the number the partner uses on their documents.\n- **Our Part #** — your catalog part number it maps to.\n- **Resolves To** — a live preview. As soon as your part number matches a real catalog part, its description appears here. If it matches nothing, a yellow **No matching part** chip shows instead.\n\nThat resolution preview is your data-quality check. A row with a 'No matching part' chip still saves — but an inbound order line using it will arrive unresolved until that part actually exists in your catalog. Use the preview to catch typos and missing parts before real orders flow.\n\n### Building the map by hand\n\nFor a handful of parts:\n\n1. Click **Add Row**. A blank row appears.\n2. Type the partner's part number in **Partner Part #**.\n3. Type your part number in **Our Part #**. Watch the **Resolves To** column confirm the match.\n4. Repeat for each pair. Remove a wrong row with its trash icon.\n5. Click **Save**. The whole map is saved and the grid reloads with fresh catalog resolution.\n\n### Importing a CSV\n\nFor a long cross-reference, don't hand-type — import it. Click **Import CSV**, choose a two-column file (Partner Part #, Our Part #), and the rows merge into the map. The import **upserts by partner number**: a partner number already in the map is updated; a new one is added. So you can re-import a corrected file without creating duplicates. After import, a confirmation message reports how many rows were new, how many were updated, and how many still have no matching part. (The companion 'Part-Number Map CSV Import' reference covers the exact file format.)\n\n### How matching actually runs (an incoming 850)\n\nWhen a customer sends a purchase order (an **850**), Forge matches each order line *before* it becomes a Sales Order line:\n\n1. The line's partner part number is looked up in **this partner's** Part-Number Map.\n2. **Mapped and resolved** → the Sales Order line is created against your catalog part. Done automatically.\n3. **Unmapped, or mapped to a number that isn't in your catalog yet** → the line is **still created**, but the partner's number is kept in the order-line notes so someone can finish the match by hand.\n\nNothing is silently dropped. An incomplete map just means more manual matching, not lost orders — which is exactly why keeping the map current pays off on every inbound document.\n\n### Scope\n\nThe Part-Number Map is intentionally a *number swap* — the 90% case. Unit-of-measure and pack-quantity translation are documented extensions, not built today. If a partner needs those, that is a configuration conversation, not something you set up in this grid.\n\n### Tips\n\n- Build the map **before** the partner starts sending live orders — then the first 850 lands clean.\n- Matching is case-insensitive, so 'widget-001' and 'WIDGET-001' resolve the same way.\n- Revisit the map whenever you add catalog parts a partner already references — those previously-unresolved rows will start resolving.","sections":[]}"""
        });

