            AppRoutes = """["/admin/edi"]""",
            Tags = """["edi","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## EDI — Deeper How-Tos\n\nThe fuller notes for someone who runs EDI day to day — reading a new partner's setup sheet, linking a partner to the right account, choosing how their documents travel, and handling the quantity gotcha that trips people up. For the everyday walkthrough, see the core EDI modules; this is the stuff you reach for when a specific partner doesn't behave like the others.\n\n## Reading a New Partner's Setup Sheet\n\nWhen a customer wants to start trading EDI with you, they send a short setup sheet. Your job is to copy a few values from it into the partner's form. Two of them go together and are worth understanding:\n\n- The partner gives you an **ID code** and a **short code that says what kind of ID it is**. Think of it like an address plus a label saying whether that address is a phone number, a company registry number, or just a code the two of you agreed on. You type both in exactly as the sheet shows them — the app stores them as-is and doesn't second-guess the partner.\n- Most small and mid-size customers just agree on a code with you rather than use a formal registry number. The form defaults to that agreed-code setting, so for many partners you can leave it and only fill in the value they gave you.\n\nIf a value on the sheet looks unfamiliar, don't overthink it — type what the partner wrote. The only real mistake is retyping it wrong, so double-check the characters. If their first documents don't match to the partner, a mistyped ID code is the first thing to check.\n\n## Linking a Partner to the Right Customer or Vendor\n\nA trading partner is an EDI relationship; a customer or vendor is the account you already have in Forge. Linking the two lets an incoming document land on the right account on its own.\n\n- Link a partner to a **customer** for the usual case — a customer sending you orders. Link to a **vendor** if you're the buyer receiving their documents. You can link to both if you sell to and buy from the same company under one EDI relationship, or to neither while you get set up.\n- The link is what puts an incoming order on the right account: when a customer's purchase order comes in, the sales order it creates is attached to the linked customer automatically. With no link, the document still reads fine but has nowhere to attach, so it waits for you to sort it out by hand.\n- The link is separate from the ID code the partner uses to address documents to you. The ID code gets their documents to *you*; the customer or vendor link decides which *account* inside Forge the order lands on. So always set the link, not just the ID code.\n\n## Choosing How a Partner's Documents Travel\n\nYou pick one way of moving documents per partner. Beyond the one-liners in the core reference, here's how to choose:\n\n- **Secure connection** — a direct, encrypted link straight to the partner, with a signed receipt coming back that proves each document arrived. No middleman. Best when you trade a lot with one partner and want proof of delivery. You set it up directly with them.\n- **Go-between service** — a service like SPS Commerce, TrueCommerce, or Cleo sits in the middle and routes documents for you. You connect to the service once and reach many partners through it. It costs a bit per document but saves you setting up each partner directly — often the easiest path when a customer already uses one.\n- **Direct connection to their system** — some large customers and marketplaces offer this instead of traditional EDI. You handle the documents the same way once they're flowing.\n- **Shared folder** — documents are dropped into folders on a secure server both sides use: yours go in one folder, theirs are picked up from another. It asks for the server address and a login, plus the two folder names, which the partner provides.\n- **Email** and **manual** — the low-automation options. Manual is the right place to start with any new partner: you upload and download by hand while you confirm their documents look right, then switch to an automated method once you trust them.\n\nChanging how a partner's documents travel is just picking a different option and entering the new details they give you. It doesn't change who the partner is, which account they're linked to, or the history of documents you've already exchanged.\n\n## The Quantity Gotcha: Units and Pack Sizes\n\nThe part-number list matches a partner's part number to yours — and that's *all* it does. It does **not** convert units or pack quantities, and this is the single most common surprise on incoming orders, so it's worth knowing cold.\n\n- If a partner orders in cases and you stock in single pieces, or their order line uses a unit (each, case, box, pallet) that differs from how you stock the part, the quantity comes through **exactly as they sent it**. An order for '5 cases' becomes a line for '5' of your part — not 5 cases' worth of pieces.\n- There's no unit conversion and no case-to-piece multiplier in EDI today. A partner who needs that is a setup conversation with your team, not something you flip on in this grid.\n- What to do about it: for any partner whose ordering unit differs from how you stock the part, glance at their applied orders before the floor fulfills them, or — better — agree with the partner that they'll order in your stocking unit. Catching it here saves a scramble later.\n","sections":[]}"""
